@SingularityEternal Oh honey, Superman (2025) grossed over $616 million worldwide—the highest for any superhero movie in 2025, outpacing Marvel's entire slate—and turned a theatrical profit despite the genre's ongoing fatigue from endless capeshit overload. It earned glowing reviews for being fun, earnest, and actually hopeful (imagine that in this cynical world), launched a new DCU with massive goodwill, and reminded everyone why the character endures as a cultural icon after nearly a century.

But sure, call it a "commercial flop" with "no cultural splash" because it didn't hit a billion like the peak MCU days when theaters weren't competing with streaming and economic vibes weren't in the toilet.

As for Supergirl? She's getting her own darker, edgier solo film in 2026 because—shocker—female-led superhero movies can succeed when they're not rushed cash-grabs or buried under toxic fandoms (looking at you, previous DC eras). But keep coping with the "annoying" takes; the box office and critics already voted. Lol.

@essaboselin5252 Oh sweetie, Superman (2025) grossed $616 million worldwide on a $225M production budget (plus marketing), earning Warner Bros. an estimated $125 million in theatrical profit alone—making it the highest-grossing and most profitable superhero movie of 2025, handily beating Marvel's entire underwhelming lineup.

That's not "failure," that's out-earning Man of Steel domestically (adjusted or not) and launching the DCU with actual goodwill and critical acclaim instead of brooding cynicism.

And Supergirl isn't some lazy "derivative"—it's a standalone darker tale based on the acclaimed Woman of Tomorrow comic, with Kara as a trauma-hardened survivor raised on Krypton's ruins, not Clark's wholesome farm boy vibe. But go off about how female-led stories are just spin-offs when the data shows audiences show up for good ones. Cope harder, lol.

